Your AI agent just refactored your checkout form. Clean diff. Confident commit message. You open the browser. The submit button is gone.

The agent never looked. It read code, edited code, declared victory -- but never opened a browser to check. This is how you get AI slop: competent code generation with zero verification. The agent can't click its own button.

"Just write E2E tests." Sure -- tests catch functional regressions. But frontend isn't just functionality. It's interaction and aesthetics. The save button that ended up below the fold. The form labels that shifted left after a grid change. The modal that opens behind the overlay. These are common-sense mistakes any human would catch in two seconds by looking at the screen. No test suite covers "the layout looks wrong." The agent needs to *see* the page, not just assert against it.

The missing piece isn't smarter generation. It's the ability to play with the result before shipping it.

```bash
agent-browser snapshot -i
```

```
@e1 button "Submit Order"
@e2 input "Email" value=""
@e3 alert "Payment failed: card declined"
```

~100 tokens. The full interactive state of a page. The AI reads this, clicks `@e1`, fills `@e2`, checks the result. No human alt-tabbing to Chrome. No "does it work now?" after every code change.

This is the tool that closed the loop.

## What I Tried Before

### Chrome DevTools MCP: 30,000 Tokens Per Call

My first attempt. Connect Claude to Chrome's debugging protocol via MCP. In theory, the AI gets full browser access.

In practice, I kept turning it off. Even after disabling audits, a single tool call consumed **30,000+ tokens**. DOM snapshots, computed styles, network waterfall -- it dumps everything. My context window filled with Chrome internals instead of the actual bug.

### Claude Chrome Extension: Permission Prompts on Localhost

The Claude browser extension is more conservative with tokens. Good. But it asks permission to interact with `localhost:5173`. My dev server. On my machine.

Every click: "Allow Claude to interact with this page?" Every form fill: same prompt. A tool that's supposed to automate the verify step shouldn't require manual approval on every action.

## Why CLIs Beat MCP for This

I've been replacing MCP servers with CLIs across the board. `gws` replaced the Google Workspace MCP. agent-browser replaced Chrome DevTools MCP. Same capabilities, fraction of the tokens. Here's why the pattern works:

**MCP loads its entire manual upfront.** Every conversation starts with thousands of tokens of tool schemas -- whether you use those tools or not. A CLI's manual is `--help`, fetched on demand for a few hundred tokens.

**Human-centric CLIs are AI-guessable.** `agent-browser click @e1` follows conventions the model has seen millions of times in training data. If it guesses wrong, the error message points to the right command. MCP tools return opaque "invalid parameters" errors.

**CLIs compose.** Pipe, redirect, chain with `&&`, wrap in scripts. MCP tools are isolated function calls. You can't `agent-browser snapshot -i | grep alert` with an MCP server.

**CLIs converge with training data.** Flag patterns, subcommands, positional args -- these are massively represented in the model's training set. MCP schemas are novel per-server. In the future, popular CLIs will be part of model training directly. No manual needed.

## agent-browser in Practice

```bash
npm install -g agent-browser
```

Four commands cover 90% of use:

```bash
agent-browser snapshot -i           # read the page (interactive elements)
agent-browser click @e4             # click by reference
agent-browser fill @e2 "hello"      # type into an input
agent-browser screenshot /tmp/s.png # visual capture
```

The snapshot returns an accessibility tree, not a DOM dump:

```
@e1 navigation "Main Menu"
@e2 link "Dashboard"
@e3 button "Submit Order"
@e4 input "Email" value="user@example.com"
@e5 alert "Payment failed: card declined"
```

The `@e1` references are stable within a page state. The AI uses them directly in the next command. No CSS selectors to construct, no XPath to guess.

## Connect to Your Own Browser

You don't need a headless browser. Open `chrome://inspect/#remote-debugging`:

<img src={chromeRemoteDebugging} alt="Chrome remote debugging settings page with 'Allow remote debugging' enabled and server running at 127.0.0.1:41175" />

Check the box. Now agent-browser connects to **your actual Chrome** -- login sessions, cookies, dev data, everything:

```bash
agent-browser --cdp-url ws://127.0.0.1:41175 snapshot -i
```

You watch the AI click buttons in the same browser you're looking at. No separate profile, no re-authentication.

## What a Feedback Loop Actually Looks Like

Without agent-browser, the AI is blind after the edit:

```
You: "Checkout validation is broken"
Claude: *reads source, fixes validator*
Claude: "I've fixed it. Can you check if it works?"
You: *opens browser, fills form, submits*
You: "Still broken, the error message doesn't show"
Claude: *reads source again, tries another fix*
Claude: "Try now?"
```

With agent-browser:

```
You: "Checkout validation is broken"
Claude: *opens page, submits empty form, sees no error*
Claude: *reads source, fixes validator*
Claude: *submits empty form again, sees error appear*
Claude: "Fixed. Required field validation was missing on email."
```

The second version has zero back-and-forth. The AI verified its own fix.

## The Landscape

I've tried Playwright CLI (too verbose for interactive use -- a full script to check if a button exists), BrowserUse (Python, heavier setup), and I'm watching Google build their own.

The `chrome-devtools-mcp` repo now ships an experimental CLI alongside the MCP server:

<img src={chromeDevtoolsMcp} alt="ChromeDevTools/chrome-devtools-mcp GitHub repo showing chrome-devtools-cli skill alongside the MCP tools" />

Google's own team is building a CLI *next to* their MCP server. The direction is clear.

## The Tradeoff: Accessibility Trees vs. Screenshots

Snapshots are semantic. The AI sees "button Submit Order", not "blue rectangle at (450, 320)." It can act on that directly.

What you lose: visual layout. The AI can't tell if two elements overlap or if spacing is wrong. For layout bugs, use `agent-browser screenshot`. For everything else -- form behavior, navigation flow, error states, data display -- the accessibility tree is faster and more precise.

## Commands Reference

```bash
# Read
agent-browser snapshot -i              # interactive elements (~100 tokens)
agent-browser snapshot -i -c           # compact mode (even fewer)
agent-browser get text @e6             # extract specific text
agent-browser console                  # browser console output
agent-browser errors                   # browser errors only

# Act
agent-browser open <url>
agent-browser click @e4
agent-browser fill @e5 "hello"
agent-browser keyboard "Enter"
agent-browser select @e7 "option-2"
agent-browser scroll down 500

# Capture
agent-browser screenshot /tmp/state.png
agent-browser screenshot --full-page /tmp/full.png

# Inspect
agent-browser cookies
agent-browser storage
agent-browser eval "document.title"
agent-browser tab list
```

100 tokens to read a page. One command to act on it. The feedback loop that frontend AI development was missing.

